\title{ebrecipe: Log-Spline Empirical Bayes Deconvolution, Shrinkage, and Selection}
\description{
\code{ebrecipe} implements the empirical Bayes workflow emphasized in Walters
(2024): estimate unit-level effects, recover a prior distribution, and use
that prior for shrinkage, ranking, and selection. The package is designed for
readers who want both a practical analysis interface and a transparent link
back to the underlying statistical workflow.
}
\details{
The package supports two complementary working styles:
\itemize{
\item a \strong{monolithic interface} built around \code{\link[=eb]{eb()}} for users who want an
end-to-end empirical Bayes analysis from precomputed estimates and standard
errors
\item a \strong{stepwise interface} built around \code{\link[=eb_input]{eb_input()}}, \code{\link[=eb_diagnose]{eb_diagnose()}},
\code{\link[=eb_standardize]{eb_standardize()}}, \code{\link[=eb_deconvolve]{eb_deconvolve()}}, \code{\link[=eb_shrink]{eb_shrink()}}, and \code{\link[=eb_classify]{eb_classify()}}
for users who want to inspect or customize each stage directly
}
}
\section{Start here}{

For most users, \code{\link[=eb]{eb()}} is the safest first entry point. If you already have
unit-level estimates and standard errors from another estimation procedure,
create an \code{eb_estimates} object with \code{\link[=eb_input]{eb_input()}} and then either continue
step by step through the Walters-style pipeline or pass those inputs to
\code{\link[=eb]{eb()}} for a single-call analysis.
}

\section{Main workflows}{

\itemize{
\item \code{\link[=eb]{eb()}} runs the complete empirical Bayes workflow for vector or summary-data
inputs.
\item \code{\link[=eb_test]{eb_test()}} adds the current testing and decision wrapper around the EB
workflow.
\item \code{\link[=eb_vam]{eb_vam()}} runs the current linear school value-added workflow.
\item \code{\link[=eb_rank]{eb_rank()}}, \code{\link[=eb_reliability]{eb_reliability()}}, and \code{\link[=eb_mse]{eb_mse()}} summarize common
post-shrinkage decisions and diagnostics.
